Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: KenolKobil, Total Kenya Shares Move

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-06-17T16:12:46Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-17/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-kenolkobil-total-kenya-are-active.html
The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-
Share Index fell for the seventh day, the longest streak of
losses since March 8, retreating 0.5 percent to 25,309.17 by the
2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, according to an e-mailed statement
from the exchange.  Namibia ’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  dropped 1.1 percent to
807.93 by the 4 p.m. close in Windhoek, the lowest since Nov.
30. Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index gained for a fourth day, the
longest rally in more than a month, rising 0.3 percent to
2,094.46 by the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis . The Ghana Stock
Exchange Composite Index advanced 0.5 percent to 1,180.64 by the
4 p.m. close in Accra. Kenya’s All-Share Index rose for a second
day, adding 0.1 percent to 71.31 by the 3 p.m. end of trading in
Nairobi.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  KenolKobil Ltd. (KNOC KN), a Kenyan fuel retailer with
operations in nine African countries, extended gains for a
fourth day, increasing 5 cents, or 0.5 percent, to 10.55
shillings, the highest close since Nov. 17. The Nairobi-based
company won a tender to supply 1.2 million barrels of crude oil
to Kenya Petroleum Refineries Ltd., the company said in an e-
mailed statement after the close yesterday.  Total Kenya Ltd. (TKNL)  ,  Total SA (FP) ’s unit in the East
African nation, fell 25 cents, or 1 percent, to 24.75 shillings,
the lowest level since October 2008. Crude dropped as much as 3
percent in  New York  on on doubts that a German willingness to
compromise on the Greek debt crisis will settle markets and spur
economic growth.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Chris Kay in London at 
